⬇ Download slides (.pptx)         📁 GitHub    ⚡ Quick Reference <p>Type: Full I/O problem (no function — write complete code with <code>input()</code> / <code>print()</code>)</p> <p>Core idea: read all lines, loop in steps of 2, swap each pair, reverse the first of each pair (which lands at an odd output position).</p> <pre><code>n = int(input())
lines = [input() for _ in range(n)]
for i in range(0, n, 2):
    if i + 1 &lt; n:
        print(lines[i + 1][::-1])   # odd output pos → reversed
        print(lines[i])              # even output pos → as-is
    else:
        print(lines[i][::-1])        # lone last line → reversed
</code></pre> <p>Key rules: - Read all lines first, then process (can't process on-the-fly) - After swapping, output positions 1, 3, 5… are reversed - A lone unpaired last line is always at an odd position → reverse it - <code>[::-1]</code> reverses any string in Python</p>
